<!--*********************************************
            Hint
**********************************************-->
<hint name="helpSection"><title>Worked Example</title>

<p>Here is a similar worked example:</p> 

<example newNameSpace>
<setup>
  <math name="e">101</math>
  <math name="d">21</math>
  <math name="p">2</math>
  <math name="k" simplify>$p $e</math>
  <math name="a" simplify>-$k / $e</math>
  <math name="exprVertexForm">$a (x - $d)^2 + $k</math>
  <math name="expr" expand simplify="numberspreserveorder">$exprVertexForm</math>
  <math name="sol1">$d + sqrt($e)</math>
  <math name="sol2">$d - sqrt($e)</math>
</setup>

  
<p><em>Solve the following equation by completing the square. Your final answer will have two solutions of the form <m>x = a \pm \sqrt{b}</m>.</em></p>


<p><me>$expr = 0</me></p>

  
<p><em><alert>Solution.</alert></em></p>

<ul>
  <li><p>The goal is to manipulate the given equation, <m>-2x^2 + 84x - 680 = 0</m>, until we have a form that looks like <m>(x \pm d)^2 =  \pm e</m>. When we arrive at this form, we can proceed to solve for <m>x</m> by taking the square root of both sides of the equation.</p> 
    <p>We start by trying to rewrite the first two terms on the left-hand side as a sum or a difference of squares.</p>
  </li>
  <li><p>We first notice that the expression on the left-hand side has a common factor of <m>-2</m>. We can first factor this out, then divide both sides of the equation by <m>-2</m>.</p>
    <md>
      <mrow>-2x^2 + 84x - 680 &= 0</mrow>
      <mrow>-2(x^2 - 42x + 340) &= 0</mrow>
      <mrow>x^2 - 42x + 340 &= 0</mrow>     
    </md>
  </li>
  <li><p>Next, we "complete the square" for the first two terms <m>(x^2 - 42x)</m>. In order to make this binomial a perfect square, we need to add <m>21^2</m>, because <m>(x^2 - 42x + 21^2) = (x - 21)^2</m>.</p>
    <p>We have to be careful here to keep our original expression unchanged. So, if we add a <m>21^2</m> inside the parentheses, we need to <em>subtract</em> a <m>21^2</m> outside the parentheses.</p>
    <md>
      <mrow>(x^2 -42x + 21^2) + 340 - 21^2 &= 0</mrow>
      <mrow>(x - 21)^2 - 101 &= 0</mrow>
    </md>
  </li>
  <li><p>A few more simplifications will allow us to isolate the <m>x</m> term:
    <md>
      <mrow>(x - 21)^2 &= 101</mrow>
      <mrow>\sqrt{(x - 21)^2} &= \sqrt{101}</mrow>
    </md>
  </p>
  <p>This last step results in our two possible solutions,
    <me>(x - 21) = \sqrt{101} \;\;\;\text{or}\;\;\;(x - 21) = - \sqrt{101}</me>
   </p>
  </li>

  <li><p>Solving each of the separate cases for <m>x</m> gives
    <me>x = 21 + \sqrt{101}\;\;\;\text{or}\;\;\;x = 21 - \sqrt{101}</me>
  </p>
  </li>
  <li><p>Next, we'll graph both solutions as a check on our work. Since we solved for <m>x</m> at the two locations where this quadratic equation is equal to zero, we have actually solved for the roots of the parabola given by <m>y = $expr</m>.</p>

<setup>
  <number name="xmin">min($d - 20, $d - sqrt($e)-20)</number>
  <number name="xmax">max($d + 20, $d + sqrt($e)+20)</number>
  <number name="ymin">min($k - 20, -20)</number>
  <number name="ymax">max($k + 20, 20)</number>
</setup>
    
  <sideBySide margins="5%" widths="30% 70%">
<div><p>Graph parabola with given equation:</p> 
  <p><m>y = </m> <mathInput name="eq1" prefill="$expr"/></p>
  
  <p>Graph proposed solutions:</p> 
  <p><m>x = </m><mathInput name="x1" prefill="$sol1"/></p>
  <p><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>or</p>
  <p><m>x = </m> <mathInput name="x2" prefill="$sol2"/></p>
  <p>Which yields roots of $r1, $r2.</p>
</div>
  
<graph name="g1" xmin="$xmin" xmax="$xmax" ymin="$ymin" ymax="$ymax">
  <function name="givenParabola">$eq1</function>
  <point name="r1" fixed styleNumber="5">($x1, 0)
    <label>$r1.coords</label>
  </point>
  <point name="r2" fixed styleNumber="5">($x2, 0)
    <label>$r2.coords</label>
  </point>
</graph>
  
</sideBySide>

  <p>The points we've plotted using our two solutions for <m>x</m> do in fact match up with the roots of the given parabola, so we know that our work is correct.</p>
  </li>
</ul>
      
</example>

</hint>
  

<!--*********************************************
            Solution
**********************************************-->
<solution>

<p><m>x = $sol1</m> or <m>x = $sol2</m></p>

<graph xmin="$xmin" xmax="$xmax" ymin="$ymin" ymax="$ymax">
  <function styleNumber="12">$expr</function>
  <point name="p1" fixed styleNumber="5">($sol1, 0)
    <label>$p1.coords</label>
  </point>
  <point name="p2" fixed styleNumber="5">($sol2, 0)
    <label>$p2.coords</label>
  </point>
</graph>
</solution>
</problem>



